Pushing commits from local to remote repo:
$ git remote add origin https://github.com/Payal1899/Devops-Learning  #points Origin to provided remote repo
@Payal1899 ➜ /workspaces/Devops-Learning/Git (main) $ git remote -v
 $git push --set-upstream origin main

 Now I have created another repo inside GIT folder on Assignment branch as earlier I ran cmd git init, so any folder with .git folder is GIT repo
 and with above cmds I have local repo Git folder in Assignment branch which points to https://github.com/Payal1899/Devops-Learning as remote repo


We can do the same for Gitlab:
$ git remote add origin-1 gitlab_repo_URL  #points Origin-1 to provided remote repo
@Payal1899 ➜ /workspaces/Devops-Learning/Git (main) $ git remote -v #shows remote repo
 $git push --set-upstream origin-1 main #pushed commits from local main to remote repo


Branches:
 @Payal1899 ➜ /workspaces/Devops-Learning/Git (main) $ git branch -a
* main
  remotes/origin/main

  Output says, there is 1 branch local main with * means currently in use, another remote for main remotes/origin/main.


  Creating new Branch:
  git branch branch_name
   Switching to new branch
   git switch branch_name


   git checkout -b branch_name # creates branch and switch to it


   these Branches get created on remote and not locally
   so in order to put it in local you need to do git pull

   when you do $git push --set-upstream origin branch_name, it pushed changes from branch_name to main as origin is pointing to remote repo for main

   now if you want branch_name should be local repo as well, switch to branch_name and do $git pull

Merging branches to main:
below command to be run from main 
   $git merge branch_name
   now if you do git push 
   it will add the changes from branch_name to main